---
description: C# / .NET house conventions - apply when creating or editing C# code.
globs: "**/*.cs"
alwaysApply: false
---

When creating or editing C# (`.cs`) files, follow the house C# conventions carried by the
`csharp` skill installed under `.cursor/skills/`: file layout, naming, member/constructor
ordering, modern C# syntax, async/await, exceptions + Result, structured logging, DI
lifetimes, and System.Text.Json. Prefer these over ad-hoc style. Target the .NET 8 / C# 12
floor, or the repo's pinned version if higher.

This rule points at the `csharp` skill alone, matching the convention gate's `.cs` owner -
deeper material (design patterns, the `dotnet` family) loads from those skills' own keywords,
not from here.

If the `csharp` skill is not loaded, hold the line on the highest-value rules: file-scoped
namespaces, one top-level type per file, `async`/`await` all the way down with no
`.Result` / `.Wait()`, and no swallowed exceptions.

This is guidance, auto-attached whenever a `.cs` file is in context (not a hard block). Other
file types have their own auto-attaching convention rules.
